  <sec sec-type="synthesis-author-response" id="s6">
    <title>Synthesis</title>
    <boxed-text position="float">
      <p>Reviewing Editor: Christie Fowler, University of California, Irvine</p>
      <p>Decisions are customarily a result of the Reviewing Editor and the peer reviewers coming together and discussing their recommendations until a consensus is reached. When revisions are invited, a fact-based synthesis statement explaining their decision and outlining what is needed to prepare a revision will be listed below. The following reviewer(s) agreed to reveal their identity: Kevin Beier.</p>
    </boxed-text>
    <p>This manuscript was reviewed by two experts in the field. Both reviewers felt that the manuscript provided valuable information for the field with the ‘SMART’ open package for R for whole brain analysis of cleared tissue. It was noted that, if user-friendly, this would be a significant advance over currently available software packages. However, the following concerns were noted:</p>
    <p>1. The major concern was that the software installation was not easy. One reviewer spent at least 4 dedicated hours trying to get the prerequisite WholeBrain to work on both windows and ubuntu machines, without success, and there wasn’t a clear path forward. As the majority of open issues (14/24) on the Github for WholeBrain related to difficulty in installation, perhaps this is a common problem.</p>
    <p>2. It was also noted that the manuscript would be strengthened by the authors demonstrating how the alignment of samples in WholeBrain is inadequate and show how SMART improves it. And/or provide cell counts of the cFos-cleared brains and alignments with different regions and make the case that SMART improves the quality/variability of analysis. Video tutorials may also help. Anything that allows the readers to assess how actually useful their package is without more validation.</p>
    <p>3. It was felt that a more thorough technical comparison to ClearMap would be uselful. WholeBrain tends to be in less wide use than ClearMap, and while it has its advantages, it would also be useful to provide a comparison of how well each of the packages works for data analysis. Some benefits are mentioned in the manuscript (e.g., ability to map incomplete brains onto a reference space), but a more comprehensive comparison would help readers to better understand the benefits of their approach over others that are available.</p>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="synthesis-author-response" id="s7">
    <title>Author Response</title>
    <p>Synthesis Statement for Author (Required): This manuscript was reviewed by two experts in the field. Both reviewers felt that the manuscript provided valuable information for the field with the ‘SMART’ open package for R for whole brain analysis of cleared tissue. It was noted that, if user-friendly, this would be a significant advance over currently available software packages. However, the following concerns were noted: We appreciate the editors and reviewers’ positive reception. Because of the double-blind formatting requirements for the initial submission, we were asked to remove documentation that would unblind the review process, including written and video tutorials. We now include these in our revision. We take the general comment on user-friendliness seriously and have spent considerable effort to increase user-friendliness and accessibility of SMART for future users. These are detailed in the specific responses to reviewer comments below, but are summarized by: 1. We have improved WholeBrain installation documentation within the manuscript (p. 8-9) and on the SMART github page (https://sgoldenlab.github.io/SMART/installation.html). 2. To facilitate quicker access to the SMART pipeline to trial SMART functions, we used Docker, a platform for software virtualization, and created a Linux-based docker image with WholeBrain and SMART pre-packaged. This provides a rapid and easy, albeit static, WholeBrain and SMART installation. 3. We have generated seven detailed video tutorials spanning WholeBrain and SMART installation through final data export and plotting (see new Supplemental Table 1). 1 1. The major concern was that the software installation was not easy. One reviewer spent at least 4 dedicated hours trying to get the prerequisite WholeBrain to work on both windows and ubuntu machines, without success, and there wasn’t a clear path forward. As the majority of open issues (14/24) on the Github for WholeBrain related to difficulty in installation, perhaps this is a common problem. We appreciate the reviewer’s comment on the difficulty associated with the installation of WholeBrain and acknowledge this is a common problem for WholeBrain users. In this revision, we have approached this from two directions. First, we have improved our written installation instructions for WholeBrain in the SMART installation page (https://sgoldenlab.github.io/SMART/installation.html). Second, we now provide a Docker image with the WholeBrain and SMART packages pre-installed as a Docker container, coupled with both written instructions as well as a detailed video tutorial (Supplemental Table 1, Video 1). We detail these installation options in newly added text (p. 8-9) in the revision. This alternative installation pipeline is recommended for those who are having serious installation issues. The docker can also be used to trial the functions that are available in SMART. Because the docker image is a “snapshot” of the current versions of both WholeBrain and SMART at the time of the image creation, any updates to these packages will not be included in the image. Further, Docker requires X-Forwarding to render certain graphical user interfaces onto the host computer. This results in a slower overall interactive experience. Therefore, we still suggest users attempt to install WholeBrain normally, if possible. However, it should now be notably easier for users to trial the use of SMART prior to dedicating effort to a full manual installation. If needed, they can also use SMART (and WholeBrain) as normal with this installation approach, although without easy updates to either package and slower GUI experience. 2. It was also noted that the manuscript would be strengthened by the authors demonstrating how the alignment of samples in WholeBrain is inadequate and show how SMART improves it. And/or provide cell counts of the cFos-cleared brains and alignments with different regions and make the case that SMART improves the quality/variability of analysis. Video tutorials may also help. Anything that allows the readers to assess how actually useful their package is without more validation. We appreciate the reviewers’ thoughtful comments on demonstrating the improved sample alignment. In this revision, we demonstrate the efficacy of the SMART “choice game” by comparing the difference between AP coordinates of images predicted to correspond to the default reference templates based on simple linear interpolation, the strategy used in base WholeBrain, and their actual coordinates following the choice game (new Fig. 3A). There were several images that differed as much as 300 microns from their predicted values, enough to cause significant difference in qualitative comparisons (Fig. 3B). We now include this direct comparison in the revised manuscript (p. 10, and new Figure 3). Further, we now also include our video tutorials for users. These include: (1) WholeBrain-SMART docker installation, (2) Pipeline Introduction, (3) Pipeline Setup, (4) Alignments using the Choice Game, (5) Interactive Registrations, (6) Segmentation and Forward Warping, and (7) Dataset manipulation and plotting (see new Supplemental Table 1 for links to videos). Combined with the new Docker-based installation option, we hope these video tutorials and simpler installation process with allow readers to better assess the utility of the SMART package for their research. 2 3. It was felt that a more thorough technical comparison to ClearMap would be uselful. WholeBrain tends to be in less wide use than ClearMap, and while it has its advantages, it would also be useful to provide a comparison of how well each of the packages works for data analysis. Some benefits are mentioned in the manuscript (e.g., ability to map incomplete brains onto a reference space), but a more comprehensive comparison would help readers to better understand the benefits of their approach over others that are available. We appreciate the reviewers’ thoughtful comments on improving our discussion of the technical comparison between 3D voxel-based pipelines like Clearmap and 2D spline-based packages like WholeBrain-SMART. We now include a more detailed technical comparison in the discussion of the resubmitted manuscript (p. 13-14). Paired with the detailed written github and video tutorials, we hope it will now be easier for potential users to identify if the SMART pipeline is appropriate for their research needs. Further paired with the Docker installation option, they can also more rapidly pilot their own data, before committing further time and resources or moving to an alternative analytical pipeline.</p>
